The Telegraph - Calcutta : Bengal
 Tuesday, March 30, 2004 				 Software to pool in poll army
 A STAFF REPORTER																								Calcutta, March 29: Not only political parties, the election planners are also embracing technology as they prepare for the 14th Lok Sabha elections. 																								The National Informatics Centre (NIC), a wing of the Union ministry of information technology, released a software today to facilitate the deployment of polling personnel in the state. 																								As per Election Commission guidelines, 50 per cent of the polling personnel in this election will have to be from other districts. The software will help in the deployment of manpower at the polling booths across the state, said Subir Roy of NIC. 																								From preparing a database of the poll personnel to their selection to form groups and maintaining a reserve team to deploying the personnel  the software will make man management easier during the elections. Developed on Visual Basic, the software will also help print appointment letters for the personnel. 																								Earlier, the district offices of NIC used to handle the allotment of poll personnel, but with the software, the process can be controlled centrally. Airport arrest																								Security personnel at Dum Dum airport arrested a youth this evening for allegedly attempting to enter a prohibited area. Subrata Das, 27, of Bhowanipore, was carrying a knife and four blades when caught trying to pass through with regular labourers.
